[5] USA (Kansas)
Date: Wed 22 Mar 2017 11:45 am
Source: The Marysville Advocate [edited]
http://www.marysvilleonline.net/news/article_b4fdb5b0-0f1c-11e7-bfeb-9f0c3389d848.html


The number of mumps cases confirmed in Marshall County was at 7 early this week, according to the Marshall County Health Department.

Investigation of potential cases is ongoing. Last week [week of 12 March] the agency reported 5 cases, and Marysville schools sent home an advisory letter to parents to watch for symptoms and to isolate potential cases. Health officials urge people who think they have symptoms to stay home and to contact a physician.

Symptoms include a few days of fever, headache, muscle ache, fatigue and loss of appetite followed by swollen salivary glands.

Kansas Department of Health and Environment issued a [Thu 9 Mar 2017] letter to the Kansas USA Wrestling organization, which is a community of youth wrestling events, to notify them that mumps transmission has been documented at several wrestling tournaments in Kansas.

KDHE "has not identified all of the sources of these mumps infections," the letter says. "This means that additional, yet-to-be-identified kids or adults may still spread the disease at other wrestling events."

People who suspect they have mumps should stay home from work, school and any social or athletic activities including wresting tournaments and practices, health officials said in the letter.

Mumps outbreaks have been documented in several Kansas counties this winter. Some surrounding states have also had a number of cases, according to KDHE.

Mumps is caused by a virus and spreads through close contact with an infected person. Mumps can occasionally cause complications, including inflammation of the testicles or ovaries, meningitis, encephalitis and deafness. Most people with mumps recover completely in a few weeks.

In addition to staying isolated when a person has mumps, the spread of virus can be prevented by:
- Washing hands often with soap and water.
- Covering mouth and nose with a tissue when coughing or sneezing, and putting used tissue in the trash can. If no tissue is available, a person can cough or sneeze into the upper sleeve or elbow, not the hands.
- Avoiding sharing drinks or eating utensils.
- Disinfecting frequently touched surfaces, such as toys, doorknobs, tables, counters.

After the introduction of the MMR (measles, mumps and rubella) vaccine, mumps became less common in the United States, KDHE reports. MMR vaccine prevents most, but not all, cases of mumps and complications caused by the disease.

Some people who receive 2 doses of MMR can still get mumps, especially when they have prolonged, close contact with someone who has the disease. If a vaccinated person does get mumps, he or she will likely have less severe illness than an unvaccinated person. Therefore the best way to reduce the chance of getting the disease is by being vaccinated with the MMR vaccine.

[Byline: Sarah Kessinger]

